\pard\pardeftab708\li340\ri0\sl276\slmult1\sa200\partightenfactor0

\fs20 \cf0 The viewer\'92s user interface mainly consists of three components: \
\pard\pardeftab708\fi340\ri0\sl276\slmult1\sa200\partightenfactor0
\cf0 The menu bar provides access to the viewer\'92s basic options.\
\pard\pardeftab708\li720\fi-360\ri850\sl276\slmult1\sa200\partightenfactor0
\cf0 -	\'93
\f2\i\b Viewer
\f1\i0\b0 \'94: Items to load / unload assets, take screenshots and open the viewer\'92s options dialog.\
\pard\pardeftab708\li720\fi-360\ri1206\sl276\slmult1\sa200\qj\partightenfactor0
\cf0 	
\fs16 * "
\f0\b Open Asset
\f1\b0 ": Displays the file system dialog where you can choose a new asset to load. Note that you can also Drag&Drop models onto the viewer panel.\
	* "
\f0\b Close Asset
\f1\b0 ": Closes the current asset and releases all resources associated with it. No action if no asset is loaded.\
	* "
\f0\b Screenshot
\f1\b0 ": Save a snapshot of the viewer to a file. The snapshot does only include the preview panel, the rest of the user interface is not visible. Saved screenshots have no watermarks. This is Open Source Software!\
	* "
\f0\b Reset View
\f1\b0 ": Reset the viewing position and direction to the default settings. This is: Camera position at 0|0|0, looking at 0|0|1.\
	* "
\f0\b Memory consumption
\f1\b0 ": Display a box with approximated memory statistics. Note that the total memory consumption needn't be equal to the physical memory allocated to the process (as displayed by Windows Task Manager). The memory consumption does only refer to the memory required for the asset itself, not for the rest of the viewer.\
	* "
\f0\b Setup file associations
\f1\b0 ": Associate all file formats which can be read by ASSIMP with the viewer. If you double click on such a file in Windows Explorer, it will be automatically opened with AssimpView.\
	* "
\f0\b Recent files
\f1\b0 ": Displays a popup menu with a list of recently opened assets. Simply click on one to reload it.\
	* "
\f0\b Clear history
\f1\b0 ": Clear the file history\
	* "
\f0\b Quit
\f1\b0 ": What do you think?\
\pard\pardeftab708\li720\fi-360\ri0\sl276\slmult1\sa200\partightenfactor0

\fs20 \cf0 - 	
\f3\i "
\f2\b Tools
\f3\b0 "
\f1\i0 : Additional utilities like stereo view, normal type.\
\pard\pardeftab708\li720\fi-360\ri1208\sl276\slmult1\sa200\qj\partightenfactor0
\cf0 	
\fs16 * "
\f2\i\b Log window
\f1\i0\b0 ": Displays the output window of the logger. Warnings are displayed in orange/yellow, errors in red, debug messages in blue and status information messages in green.\
	* "
\f2\i\b Save log to file
\f1\i0\b0 ": Saves the contents of the log window to a file.\
	* "
\f2\i\b Clear log
\f1\i0\b0 " Clear the contents of the log window\
	* "
\f2\i\b Original normals
\f1\i0\b0 ": Specifies that the original normal set from the model file is used in the preview. Normally this is the best choice, as smoothing groups etc. are handled correctly, but there are many models out there which have invalid or corrupt normal sets. However, if a model has no normal set, ASSIMP computes a smooth normal set for it. "Original normals" is in this case equivalent to "Smooth normals"\
	* "
\f2\i\b Smooth normals
\f1\i0\b0 ": Specifies that a smoothed, per-vertex, normal set is used in the preview window.\
	* "
\f2\i\b Hard normals
\f1\i0\b0 ": Specifies that a hard, per-face, normal set is used\
	* "
\f2\i\b Flip normals
\f1\i0\b0 ": Flip all normal vectors\
\pard\pardeftab708\li720\fi-360\ri850\sl276\slmult1\sa200\qj\partightenfactor0

\fs20 \cf0 -	\'93
\f2\i\b Background
\f1\i0\b0 \'94: Set the background color or use a texture (cube maps are supported as skyboxes) as background image for the viewer.\
\pard\pardeftab708\li720\fi-360\ri1208\sl276\slmult1\sa200\qj\partightenfactor0
\cf0 	
\fs16 * "
\f2\i\b Set color
\f1\i0\b0 ": Displays a color picker where you can choose a new background color for the viewer.\
	* "
\f2\i\b Load skybox
\f1\i0\b0 ": Opens a file system dialog where you can select a skybox as background image. Accepted file formats are: *.dds, *.hdr.\
	* "
\f2\i\b Load texture
\f1\i0\b0 ": Opens a file system dialog where you can select a texture as background image. If the format of the texture doesn't fit to the proportions of the preview window, the texture will be stretched. \
\pard\pardeftab708\li720\fi-12\ri1208\sl276\slmult1\sa200\qj\partightenfactor0
\cf0 Accepted file formats are: *.jpg;*.png;*.tif;*.tga;*.dds;*.hdr;*.ppm;*.bmp\
