\fs20 \cf0 The side panel \'93
\f3\i Statistics
\f1\i0 \'94 displays rendering statistics. The meanings of the fields change if you change between normal, node and texture or material view mode.\
\pard\pardeftab708\li340\ri1474\sl276\slmult1\sa200\qj\partightenfactor0
\cf0 Normal view mode:\
\pard\pardeftab708\li340\ri1208\sl276\slmult1\sa200\qj\partightenfactor0
\cf0 	
\fs16 * "
\f2\i\b Verts
\f1\i0\b0 ": Number of unique vertices in the asset\
	* "
\f2\i\b Faces
\f1\i0\b0 ": Number of faces (= triangles) in the asset\
	* "
\f2\i\b Nodes
\f1\i0\b0 ": Number of nodes in the scenegraph, including the root node\
\pard\pardeftab708\li708\fi-368\ri1208\sl276\slmult1\sa200\qj\partightenfactor0
\cf0 	* "
\f2\i\b Mats:
\f1\i0\b0 " Number of different materials found in the mesh. Most loaders remove unreferenced materials.\
\pard\pardeftab708\li700\ri1208\sl276\slmult1\sa200\qj\partightenfactor0
\cf0 * "
\f2\i\b Mesh
\f1\i0\b0 ": Number of sub meshes. Each mesh has only one material 	assigned, so this number is in most cases equal to or higher than the number of materials.\
* "
\f2\i\b Shd
\f1\i0\b0 ": Number of unique shaders created for this asset. If AssimpView detects that two materials can be rendered using the same Shader code, but with different parameterizations, it doesn't create the Shader twice. Most engines do so, too. This allows you to approximate the rendering const for the asset.\
* "
\f2\i\b Time
\f1\i0\b0 ": Time required for loading, in seconds. This time is the raw time the process spent in Assimp loading the model itself, it does not include texture loading, Shader compilation...\
\pard\pardeftab708\li340\ri1474\sl276\slmult1\sa200\qj\partightenfactor0

\fs20 \cf0 Texture view mode:\
\pard\pardeftab708\li340\ri1208\sl276\slmult1\sa200\qj\partightenfactor0
\cf0 	
\fs16 * "
\f2\i\b Width
\f1\i0\b0 ": Width of the texture, in pixels\
	* "
\f2\i\b Height
\f1\i0\b0 ": Height of the texture in pixels\
\pard\pardeftab708\li708\ri1208\sl276\slmult1\sa200\qj\partightenfactor0
\cf0 * "
\f2\i\b Format
\f1\i0\b0 ": Format of the texture. This will normally be ARGB8. Other possible values are: RRG565, ARGB16f, ARGB32F. Embedded textures are always converted to ARGB8 format, even if they\'92re stored in the file with a higher color depth.\
\pard\pardeftab708\li340\fi368\ri1208\sl276\slmult1\sa200\qj\partightenfactor0
\cf0 * "
\f2\i\b UV
\f1\i0\b0 ": UV channel used by the texture. Normally this is the first channel.\
\pard\pardeftab708\li340\ri1208\sl276\slmult1\sa200\qj\partightenfactor0
\cf0 	* \'93
\f2\i\b MIPs
\f1\i0\b0 ": Number of MIP map levels created for the texture\
\pard\pardeftab708\li708\ri1208\sl276\slmult1\sa200\qj\partightenfactor0
\cf0 * \'93
\f2\i\b Blend
\f1\i0\b0 ": Strength of the texture. The color value obtained from the texture is multiplied with this factor to calculate the final color.\
* "
\f2\i\b Op
\f1\i0\b0 ": Blend operation used to combine this texture with the corresponding material color (or the previous texture).\
\pard\pardeftab708\li340\ri1474\sl276\slmult1\sa200\qj\partightenfactor0

\fs20 \cf0 Always visible:\
\pard\pardeftab708\li700\ri1208\sl276\slmult1\sa200\qj\partightenfactor0

\fs16 \cf0 * "
\f2\i\b FPS
\f1\i0\b0 ": Current frame rate, in frames per second. Note that this number is not really exact. It is only an approximation to the real frame rate. The maximum frame rate will never be reached since there is a 10 ms blocker included (to work around good our old AMD timing bug)\
\pard\pardeftab708\li340\ri0\sl276\slmult1\sa200\partightenfactor0

